{{- /*
config-secrets-key-ensure.tmpl — GET-OR-CREATE the machine-local AES key that
encrypts the secrets prompted by .chezmoi.toml.tmpl (luksPassphraseCipher /
mokPasswordCipher). Returns the key (creating it in the user keyring, Secret
Service, service=chezmoi-config-secrets / user=<username>, if absent), or the
empty string when the keyring is unreachable.

WHY THIS EXISTS — the ordering trap. chezmoi renders the config template
(.chezmoi.toml.tmpl), where it PROMPTS for and ENCRYPTS these secrets, BEFORE
it runs the read-source-state.pre hook (.install-prerequisites.{sh,ps1}) that
also seeds the key. So on a fresh machine's FIRST `chezmoi init`, the hook has
not run yet when the prompt fires: a plain `keyring get` would come back empty,
$secretsKey would be "", and a typed passphrase would hit the loud `fail`
(exactly the "keyring locked or unreachable" abort seen on a brand-new host).
Creating the key HERE, during the same render and just before the prompt reads
it, is what makes the first init succeed — the hook seeding is now only an early
best-effort / Windows-parity path, not the thing the first prompt depends on.

Its read-only sibling .chezmoitemplates/config-secrets-key.tmpl is the one the
DECRYPT consumers (run_onchange_after_luks-tpm2, run_onchange_before_ubuntu)
use: they must NOT create a fresh key, because a host that stored a cipher but
lost its keyring entry would then get a NEW random key that cannot decrypt the
old ciphertext. Create only where a secret is being stored (this file); read
only where one is being decrypted (the sibling).

LINUX-ONLY, matching the sibling and the hook: both consumers are Linux-gated,
and macOS's keyring backend (go-keyring drives /usr/bin/security) can escalate
to a BLOCKING SecurityAgent dialog on a locked keychain, hanging a headless
render forever. On any other OS this renders the empty string, i.e. the
secret-absent skip path.

FAIL-SOFT throughout. The whole `sh -c` always exits 0 (the final `printf` is
its last command; every keyring call is guarded with `|| true` / `|| k=`), so
`output` never turns a locked/absent Secret Service into a render error the way
the built-in `keyring` function would. A `timeout 10` on each keyring call turns
a Secret Service prompter that never answers into a skip instead of a stuck
render. `.chezmoi.executable` (not a bare `chezmoi`) keeps this working when the
running binary is not on PATH.

Rotation/loss: see the sibling's header — a lost or rotated entry cannot decrypt
previously stored ciphertexts. Recover by re-prompting with
`chezmoi init --data=false` (or deleting the *Cipher keys and re-running init).
*/ -}}
{{- if eq .chezmoi.os "linux" -}}
{{-   $cmd := printf "e=%q u=%q s=chezmoi-config-secrets; k=$(timeout 10 \"$e\" secret keyring get --service=\"$s\" --user=\"$u\" 2>/dev/null || true); if [ -z \"$k\" ]; then k=$(head -c 32 /dev/urandom | base64 -w0 2>/dev/null || true); [ -n \"$k\" ] && { timeout 10 \"$e\" secret keyring set --service=\"$s\" --user=\"$u\" --value=\"$k\" >/dev/null 2>&1 || k=; }; fi; printf '%%s' \"$k\"" .chezmoi.executable .chezmoi.username -}}
{{-   output "sh" "-c" $cmd | trim -}}
{{- end -}}
